Boyd, &quot;Lost Original&quot;, 448&lt;U+2013&gt;50. Boyd argued that if a document was signed on July 4--which he thought unlikely--it would have been the Fair Copy, and probably would have been signed only by Hancock and Thomson.â©
Ritz, &quot;From the Here&quot;, speculates that the Fair Copy was immediately sent to the printer so that copies could be made for each member of Congress to consult during the debate. All of these copies were then destroyed, theorizes Ritz, to preserve secrecy.â©
